Serverless, containers, and E-C-2: the trade-off.

Module three gave you the canonical web tier: E-C-2 instances behind a load balancer, fronted by an Auto Scaling Group. It works. So why would you ever choose anything else? Three pressures push real workloads off pure E-C-2. The first is bursty demand: an Auto Scaling Group ramps too slowly, and you pay for the idle floor between spikes. The second is operational surface: you don't want to patch operating systems or bake A-M-Is for code that runs one second once a minute. And the third is runtime packaging: you want the exact same binary, with the same dependencies, running on your laptop, in C-I, and in production.

Two models answer those pressures. Serverless: you write the code, and AWS handles provisioning, patching, scaling, and high availability. You pay only for the compute your code actually uses, and idle costs nothing. Containers: your code, runtime, and dependencies packaged into one portable image that runs anywhere a container engine exists. AWS runs containers three ways: native with E-C-S, Kubernetes-flavoured with E-K-S, or fully serverless with Fargate.

The trade-off is steady. Serverless wins on event-driven, intermittent, or unpredictable work, thanks to automatic near-instant scaling, no idle cost, and per-request pricing. Long-running, stateful, or sustained-C-P-U work belongs on E-C-2 or containers, because at high steady utilisation, per-invocation pricing loses to per-hour. This module walks Lambda first, then the container services, E-C-S, Fargate, and E-K-S, and closes with the decision tree.
